John Edward: language skills are vital for citizens of the world
The independent schools in Scotland have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding results in examinations, which is further enhanced by individual and collective success in sport, the arts, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS, for short), strive to deliver the best possible service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare their pupils for further education, for the career they choose and for the place they will occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a curriculum, modern languages are observed to remain popular and sought after in schools.
As Nelson Mandela said: "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the message will get to his head.
If you speak to them in their language, you reach their heart.
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we look at the recent results of this year &apos; s examinations, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables, with the pass rates at independent schools being the highest.
Overall, 68 per cent of pupils studying foreign languages achieved an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centres that make up the SCIS, showed that 72 per cent of students achieved an A in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of those studying German, 69 per cent of those studying French and 63 per cent of those studying Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a fundamental skill that will be needed by children and young people in the future without a doubt.
Today, languages are considered to be on the same level as the STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere else.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 per cent of the reasons given by employers for difficulties in filling jobs were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly indispensable for preparing young people for their future careers.
The potential for employment requiring language skills is increasing, making these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career path someone chooses, if he or she has learned a second language, he or she will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a skill like this, which will last a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people in foreign countries will automatically put that person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 per cent of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and it was also established that the only language spoken by a two-figure percentage, 15 per cent, was French.
For this reason, investing in language learning is important for today &apos; s children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, they will be equipped to have better opportunities for quality employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught in different schools.
Some centres will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the more important languages for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child &apos; s interests, independent schools will always offer a choice of languages taught by specialist staff.
Independent schools in Scotland focus all their efforts on providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may hold.
It is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages must be considered "competences for international communication."
The independent sector will continue to offer these choices, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It is only fair.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Independent Colleges Council
