Harvard students take a course on how to sleep enough
Thanks to a new course being taught this year at Harvard University, all college students are now sleeping more in an attempt to fight the growing culture of all-night cramming while drinking coffee.
A professor discovered that the students at the number one university in the world often have no idea about basic self-care.
The course, believed to be the first of its kind in the United States, was designed by Charles Czeisler, a sleep medicine professor at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital.
His motivation for starting the course came after giving a talk on how sleep deprivation affects learning.
At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and asked why she was only hearing about this now, in her final year.
He said that no one had ever spoken to him about the importance of the dream, which surprised me, &quot; he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first offered this year, explains to students the basic concepts of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university &apos; s health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were hardly sleeping during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, athletic shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of establishing a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are informed that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
After that, an icon on campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
We know that it will not change the behaviour of students overnight.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco,” added Professor Czeisler.
He stated that the culture of "pulling an all-nighter" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Getting enough sleep and a good night &apos; s sleep should be &quot; the secret weapon &quot; of students to combat stress, tiredness and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation makes the brain feel hungry, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the whole campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler &apos; s recommendation is that students set an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by screens of electrical appliances and LED, which can alter circadian rhythms, and thus end up having problems falling asleep.
