Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that culminated in the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter, which has since become a pillar of science, was also a pillar of pop culture, as in the 1950 film &quot; The Singing Hills &quot;, with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans playing the apparently incompatible roles of cowboy scientists:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, it's used to find radioactive minerals, like uranium.
When you put on the earphones, you can hear the effect of the radioactivity of the minerals”.
Evans: "It's like a radio!"
Hans Geiger died in 1945, at the age of 63.
But the invention that bears his name is still alive.
