The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, carried out in a Scottish Highland county, seeks to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that all that is learned will shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and soprano pipistrelle bats, as well as Daubenton &apos; s bats and long-eared brown bats in the gardens of Inverewe in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in strategic locations on the property to track bat activity during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Experts will analyse the sounds on the recordings to discover the frequency of the calls of the bats and what species make them.
A report and map of the habitat will then be produced to create a detailed image of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they use them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of grasslands and how forests should be managed for bats and other associated species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from construction and development that affect their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and power lines can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide-treated building materials and other chemical treatments, and attacks by domestic cats.
The bats are not actually blind,
They are nocturnal hunters, and their hearing is more useful than their eyesight in catching their prey.
They use a sophisticated technique of ecolocation that locates ants and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the matter of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts, who carry out regular surveys, nest inspections and, on occasion, rescues.
The charity has even opened the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
"We have a fantastic bat roost here at Threave," he said.
We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there are still many things unknown about bats, so the work we are doing here and elsewhere will help us to understand better what they need to develop."
It emphasizes the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance work inside the property, as a breeding colony could be unintentionally destroyed and 400 breeding females and young could be killed, which would wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, or to destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we know nothing about their populations."
