The trade war between the United States and China could benefit Beijing
The first salvos of the trade war between the United States and China were deafening, and although the battle is far from over, a rupture between the countries could benefit Beijing, according to experts.
President Donald Trump of the United States issued the first warning in early 2018 when he imposed tariffs on major Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs on $200 billion (£150 billion) worth of goods, which will tax half of the goods that come into the United States from China.
In all cases, Beijing has retaliated with equivalent measures, recently applying a 5-10 per cent tariff on $60 billion worth of American products.
China has pledged to match the attacks of the United States, and it is unlikely that the second largest economy in the world will soon back down.
To back down would be to concede to the demands, but to submit publicly to the United States would be too humiliating for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Even so, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards right, the pressures of the US trade war could help China in the long run by reducing the interdependence between the two economies.
The fact that a rapid policy decision in Washington or Beijing could set the stage for a sudden collapse in the economy in either country is in fact far more dangerous than has been recognized so far, said Abigail Grace, associate fellow at the Center for New American Security focused on Asia issues.
