Update on red tide: Reductions in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FFWCC) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular bloom conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends approximately 130 miles along the coast from Pinellas County to the south to Lee County to the north.
Irregular parcels can be found as far as 10 miles inland from the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer than last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, medium concentrations were reported in Pinellas County and on its coast, low concentrations were reported on the coast of Hillsborough County, low to high concentrations were reported on the bottom in Manatee County, low to high concentrations were reported on the bottom in Sarasota County and on its coast, low to high concentrations were reported on the bottom in Charlotte County, low to high concentrations were reported on the bottom in Lee County and on its coast, and low concentrations were reported in Collier County.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue to be received in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No reports of respiratory irritation have been received in the northwest part of Florida during the past week.
